711099f-a.title: Manhattan: 11th Street (West) - 4th Street
711099f-a.text:
242-208 West 11th Street, aouth sice, from east of 4th Street to
Seventh Avenue South.
The North Baptist Church (1882) is shown at 236-2 West 11th Street,
and the Church of St. John the Evangelist (Protestant Episcopal,
built 1856) at 220, at the S.W. corner of Waverly Place. A bit
of St. Vincent's Hospital, on the N.E. corner of Seventh Avenue
and the true West 11th Street, is visible in the background.
Mey 2O, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

711108f-a.title: Manhattan: 11th Street (West) - 4th Street
711108f-a.text:
11th Street (oiginally Hammond Street), at S.W. corner of 4th Street
(originally Lord knows what1), Greenwich Village. 258 West 11th
Street, the little one-story studio adjoining the corner, is
supposed to be really quite old ('very old" in Greenwich Village
weans about 1820 or earlier).
May 20, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

710914f-a.title: Manhattan: 4th Street (West) - 11th Street
710914f-a.text:
279-281 West 4th Street, adjoining the S.E. corner of 11th Street
(formerly Hammond Street). The Ship Shape Inn, at 281, is a
typical Greenwich Village restaurant.
May 12, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
